## Mac live command

Receiver address posted for Linux sender:

```text
192.168.1.15:47044
```

Receiver command:

```sh
cargo run -q -p madobectl -- \
  video-smoke receive \
  --bind 0.0.0.0:47044 \
  --evidence-dir evidence/m3-cross-device-video-smoke/macos
```

Receiver result:

```text
video-smoke receive bind=0.0.0.0:47044 peer=192.168.1.15:52212 payload_bytes=84 sha256=51945e4cd903e28019fbbfbe74572b5d836f6ef1184cb782b142aba1d5201875 status=passed
```

Mac-side validation boundary:

- Receiver-side sample validation passed.
- The observed peer address matches the Mac host address (`192.168.1.15`), so this Mac evidence alone does not prove Linux host sender provenance.
- Linux sender logs are required before the node can be completed as a cross-device validation.

## Linux live sender command

The first Mac receiver result was an accidental Mac-local sender run caused by
shell quoting in the coordination comment. The real Linux-host sender was run
after Mac restarted the receiver and posted `192.168.1.15:47044`.

Sender command:

```sh
nix develop -c cargo run -q -p madobectl -- \
  video-smoke send \
  --addr 192.168.1.15:47044 \
  --sample evidence/m2-nvenc-encode-sample/sample-av1.ivf \
  --evidence-dir evidence/m3-cross-device-video-smoke/linux
```

Captured logs:

- `linux/sender-cli.out`
- `linux/sender-cli.err`
- `linux/sender.log`
- `linux/sender-timeline.json`

Sender result:

```text
video-smoke send addr=192.168.1.15:47044 payload_bytes=84 sha256=51945e4cd903e28019fbbfbe74572b5d836f6ef1184cb782b142aba1d5201875 status=sent
```
